Step-by-Step Explanation

1. orb.string_to_object(...)
============================
org.omg.CORBA.Object obj = orb.string_to_object(
    "corbaloc:iiop:localhost:1050/Hello"
);

✅ What it does:
Converts a string (URL) into a CORBA object reference

Understanding the corbaloc URL
corbaloc:iiop:localhost:1050/Hello

Breakdown:

Part	            Meaning
corbaloc:	        CORBA location protocol
iiop:	            Internet Inter-ORB Protocol
localhost	        Server machine
1050	            Port number
/Hello	          	Object name

This directly points to the server object.
Key Idea
Instead of using a naming service, you're saying:

“I already know where the server is—connect directly.”

2. (Commented Line)
   ================
// ncRef.rebind(ncRef.to_name("Hello"), href);
✅ What it means:
This line is for Naming Service
It binds the object name "Hello" to a reference

But it's commented out because:
You are NOT using naming service here

3. HelloHelper.narrow(obj)
==========================
Hello helloRef = HelloHelper.narrow(obj);

✅ What it does:
Converts generic CORBA object → specific Hello type

Similar to type casting:

(Hello) obj   // but CORBA uses narrow()
Why narrow() is Needed?

string_to_object() returns:

org.omg.CORBA.Object

But you need:

Hello

So narrow() safely converts it 

Analogy
Step	              Real Life
corbaloc URL	      Exact address of a shop 
string_to_object	  Getting shop location
narrow()	          Entering the correct department

corbaloc vs Naming Service
===========================  
    Feature	          	Corbaloc	          Naming Service
    Setup	            Simple	              Requires service
    Flexibility	      	Low	                  High
    Use case	        Direct access	      Large systems


Final Flow
Client
  ↓
corbaloc URL
  ↓
ORB connects to server
  ↓
Gets generic object
  ↓
narrow() → Hello object
  ↓
Call methods on server


